      { id: "q282", category: Category.READING, questionText: "Based on the passage, the reader can conclude that", options: ["Mrs. Peters and Mrs. Hale are old friends.", "Mrs. Peters and Mrs. Hale both know Mrs. Wright very well.", "Mrs. Peters and Mrs. Hale don’t know each other very well.", "Neither Mrs. Peters nor Mrs. Hale like Mrs. Wright.", "Neither Mrs. Peters nor Mrs. Hale have children."], correctAnswer: 2, explanation: "Their conversation reveals they don't know much about each other (e.g., asking if she knew John Wright)." },
      { id: "q283", category: Category.READING, questionText: "Mrs. Hale says she wishes she had come to Mrs. Wright’s house because", options: ["she realizes that Mrs. Wright must have been lonely.", "she enjoyed Mr. Wright’s company.", "she always felt at home in the Wright’s house.", "she realizes how important it is to keep good relationships with one’s neighbors.", "she had a lot in common with Mrs. Wright."], correctAnswer: 0, explanation: "She says 'It would be lonesome for me sitting here alone... I wish I had come over'." },
      { id: "q284", category: Category.READING, questionText: "According to Mrs. Hale, what sort of man was Mr. Wright?", options: ["gentle and loving", "violent and abusive", "honest and dependable", "quiet and cold", "a strict disciplinarian"], correctAnswer: 3, explanation: "She describes him as 'hard' and 'like a raw wind'." },
      { id: "q285", category: Category.READING, questionText: "In lines 60–62, Mrs. Hale suggests that Mrs. Wright", options: ["had become even more like a bird than before.", "had grown bitter and unhappy over the years.", "was too shy to maintain an intimate friendship.", "must have taken excellent care of her bird.", "was always singing and flitting about."], correctAnswer: 1, explanation: "She says Mrs. Wright was 'real sweet and pretty' but 'How she did change', implying a negative change due to the 'hard' husband." },
      { id: "q286", category: Category.READING, questionText: "The phrase take up her mind in line 64 means", options: ["worry her.", "make her angry.", "refresh her memory.", "keep her busy.", "make her think."], correctAnswer: 3, explanation: "They want to give her the quilt to keep her busy/occupied." },
      { id: "q287", category: Category.READING, questionText: "It can be inferred that Mrs. Wright", options: ["got the bird as a present for her husband.", "was forced into marrying Mr. Wright.", "loved the bird because it reminded her of how she used to be.", "had a pet bird as a little girl.", "fought often with Mr. Wright."], correctAnswer: 2, explanation: "Mrs. Hale says Mrs. Wright 'was kind of like a bird herself... sweet and pretty'." },
      { id: "q288", category: Category.READING, questionText: "When the women share a look of growing comprehension, of horror (line 83), they realize that", options: ["Mrs. Wright killed the bird.", "Mr. Wright killed the bird, and Mrs. Wright killed him.", "they would get in trouble if the sheriff found out they were looking around in the kitchen.", "there’s a secret message hidden in the quilt.", "they might be Mrs. Wright’s next victims."], correctAnswer: 1, explanation: "The broken cage and dead bird suggest Mr. Wright killed it, providing the motive for Mrs. Wright to kill him." },
      { id: "q289", category: Category.READING, questionText: "The stage directions in lines 83–86 suggest that", options: ["the women are mistaken in their conclusion.", "the women will tell the men what they found.", "the women will confront Mrs. Wright.", "the women will keep their discovery a secret.", "the men had been eavesdropping on the women."], correctAnswer: 3, explanation: "Mrs. Hale slips the box under quilt pieces to hide it from the men." }
