      { id: "q293", category: Category.READING, questionText: "From Passage 2, it can be inferred that Dr. Moreau is what sort of scientist?", options: ["artistic", "calculating and systematic", "careless, haphazard", "famous, renowned", "materialist"], correctAnswer: 1, explanation: "He speaks of 'systematically' investigating, having 'scientific knowledge of the laws of growth', and detailed explanations." },
      { id: "q294", category: Category.READING, questionText: "These things that the narrator refers to in Passage 2, line 35 are", options: ["Siamese twins.", "inquisitors.", "pigs.", "creatures Moreau created.", "tyrants and criminals."], correctAnswer: 3, explanation: "He is referring to the 'creatures you have seen' mentioned at the start." },
      { id: "q295", category: Category.READING, questionText: "From the passage, it can be inferred that Dr. Moreau", options: ["does not inflict pain upon animals when he experiments on them.", "has caused great pain to the creatures he has experimented on.", "is unable to experience physical pain.", "is searching for a way to eliminate physical pain.", "has learned to feel what an animal feels."], correctAnswer: 1, explanation: "The narrator asks 'Where is your justification for inflicting all this pain?'" },
      { id: "q296", category: Category.READING, questionText: "Based on the information in the passages, Dr. Moreau is like Victor Frankenstein in that he also", options: ["used dead bodies in his experiments.", "wanted his creations to worship him.", "made remarkable discoveries.", "kept his experiment a secret from everyone.", "had a specific justification for his pursuit of knowledge."], correctAnswer: 2, explanation: "Both made breakthroughs: Frankenstein creating life, Moreau transforming animals." },
      { id: "q297", category: Category.READING, questionText: "Frankenstein would be most upset by Dr. Moreau’s", options: ["indifference to suffering.", "arrogance.", "great achievements.", "education of animals.", "choice of the human form."], correctAnswer: 0, explanation: "Frankenstein was horrified by his own 'torture of living animals' (line 53) while Moreau considers pain 'such a little thing'." },
      { id: "q298", category: Category.READING, questionText: "Which of the following best expresses Frankenstein’s and Moreau’s attitudes toward science?", options: ["Both believe science can be dangerous.", "Frankenstein believes science should have a tangible application; Moreau believes scientific knowledge should be sought for its own sake.", "Frankenstein believes scientists should not harm living creatures in an experiment; Moreau believes it is acceptable to inflict pain on other creatures.", "Both men believe scientists should justify their work.", "Both men believe the greatest discoveries often take place in secrecy."], correctAnswer: 1, explanation: "Frankenstein wanted to 'pour a torrent of light' (benefit), Moreau just wanted knowledge 'as an end' in itself." }
